04 - ggplot2 - some advanced exercises

Author

Juan Garbayo - DV Course - 2023 (Dataset by Prof. Pablo Monfort)

Important note

These exercises combine both complex visualization concepts and some data wrangling that could be difficult and are sometimes beyond the fundamentals explained in class. They are provided for students with an interest in the topic an example of syntax of complex graphs.

Do not feel frustrated if you do not manage to solve them.

You are supossed to surf the web in order to find the necessary commands to solve them.

The solution to these exercises is also provided.

MY RECOMMENDATION: spend around 20-25 minutes on each exercise. If you do not manage to solve it in this time frame, look at the in-detail solution and understand every detail.

  1. The way to write an absolute path is system dependent. Google how get the absolute path to a Folder on a Windows… Mac… Linux…

BP. 1 - colorRampPalette() - categoricals, high cardinality and colors.

When a categorical variable has many values, it becomes increasingly difficult to find a color palette that has one color for each value. The commands below load the default sequential and qualitative palettes used in ggplot. Note that, at most, they have 12 different colors. Therefore, for a categorical variable with high cardinality (many different values), they would be insufficient.

# Choose among the built-in discrete sequential palletes
library(RColorBrewer)

# Display sequential palettes to pick one among them
display.brewer.all(type = "seq")

# Display qualitative palettes to pick one among them
display.brewer.all(type = "qual")

A possible solution is to use the function colorRampPalette() to interpolate already existing palettes and expand their number of colors. It is your task to research how this function works.

We are going to consider the following three palettes as basis palettes to be interpolated:

# Rainbow flag palette
pride_palette <- 
  c("Life" = "#E40303", "Healing" = "#FF8C00", "Sunlight" = "#FFED00", 
    "Nature" = "#008026", "Serenity" = "#004dff", "Spirit" = "#750787")

# Alternative qualitative palette (template taken from colorbrewer2.com
alt_base_palette <-
  c('#a6cee3','#1f78b4','#b2df8a','#33a02c','#fb9a99','#e31a1c',
    '#fdbf6f','#ff7f00','#cab2d6','#6a3d9a','#ffff99','#b15928')

# ggplots palette Set3 (qualitative)
set3_palette <- 
  brewer.pal(n = 12, name = "Set3") # library(RColorBrewer) loaded at the top

Your task is to produce the figures below. Let us describe their data content and then their colors.

Data content:

Then produce the graphs below:

  • The rest of the graphs require you to itnerpolate the given color scales using colorRampPalette()

BP. 2 case_when()

Research how the function case_when() from the library dplyr (loaded along tidyverse) works.

Using case_when() and after filtering for shipments paid in Euros, classify each shipment in the following categories:

  • cheap - Price_per_Item lower than 50 euros.
  • regular`` -Price_per_Item` between 50 and 150 euros.
  • expensive - Price_per_Item between 150 and 300 euros.
  • extra expensive - Price_per_Item greater than 300 euros.

BP. 3

  • Create a column that classifies the shipments in each country in 4 categories (you need to use quantile())
    1. Shipments with a Price_per_Item below or equal the 25 quantile of prices - these will be cheap
    2. Shipments with a Price_per_Item between the 25 and 50 quantile of prices - these will be regular
    3. Shipments with a Price_per_Item between the 50 and 75 quantile of prices - these will be expensive
    4. Shipments with a Price_per_Item between 75 and 100 of prices - these will be extra expensive
  • Compute
    1. The total income generated in each country for each combination of item and the price ranges above. Note that each Item can have multiple price ranges! (the same generic Item can have multiple prices)
    2. The percentege of the total income generated within the country that each combination of item and price_range represent within the country.
    3. Within each country and price range, rank order the items from greatest to lowest income generated creating a new column using row_number
    4. Store the result in an aux dataframe.

Then produce the following graph indicating the percentage of total income generated by each price range for each country:

BP. 4

Starting from the output of the previous question consider that, many times, most of the sales revenue is generated by small subset of products.

Using the rank column generated in the previous question, filter to have, for each country, only the 5 items in each price category (cheap, regular, expensive, extra expensive) that generate the most income within that category. Then aggregate their percentage contributions for each combination of country and price category and store the result in a new auxiliar dataset called aux_5best. Do not delete aux, you need bot aux and aux_5best.

Subsequently, add a single geom_point() layer to your previous graph to indicate where the sum of the 5 most relevant items stands within each bar (expected output below):

NOTE: specifying data you can feed a new dataframe to a specific geom_() later. You can also override the aesthetics for that particular geom specifying the aestherics as the argument mapping.

BP. 5

The previous graph is nice, but we can make it nicer. A better way to depict that information would be using dodged bar plots as in the figure below:

To attain this:

  1. Create a new auxiliary dataframe similar to aux_5best but aggregate all items. Call it aux_allitems
  2. Use left_join() between aux_allitems and aux_5best to produce a dataframe that looks like this (code given to you, feel free to research how left_join works):
lj <- left_join(x = aux_allitems,
                y = aux_5best,
                by = c("Sent_To", "p_range"))

lj
